# Laravel and PHP Implementation Standards

Apply these standards for backend work in this Laravel 12 project.
Prioritize consistency with the current architecture: single-action controllers, Inertia responses, service-oriented domain logic, and enum-driven modeling.

## Code Comments and Readability

- Do not add obvious comments or docblocks that restate code.
- Add comments only when the intent or business reason is non-obvious.
- Do not add variable docblocks unless explicitly requested.

## PHP Preferences

- Prefer `match` over `switch` when possible.
- Place all new enums in `app/Enums`.
- If an enum exists for a domain value, use enum cases (or `->value` where required) instead of raw strings.
- Avoid one-time temporary variables such as `$currentUser = auth()->user()` if used only once.

## Enum + Database Consistency

- If a column represents enum values, set migration defaults from enum cases.
- Add model casts for enum-backed fields in `$casts`.
- Keep enums, migration defaults, seed data, and tests aligned to the same enum source.

## Controllers, Services, and Routes

- Keep controllers slim; move non-trivial business logic into service classes.
- If a service is used in only one controller method, inject it into that method.
- If a service is used in multiple methods in the same controller, inject through constructor.
- Single-action controllers must expose `__invoke()`.
- Keep route definitions explicit and aligned with existing `*Action` naming.
- Do not create controller actions that only return a Blade view; use `Route::view()` for pure Blade pages.

## Laravel Style Conventions

- Prefer Laravel helpers over facades when equivalent helpers exist:
  - `auth()->id()` over `Auth::id()`
  - `redirect()->route()` over `Redirect::route()`
  - `str()->slug()` over `Str::slug()`
- Do not use `whereKey()` / `whereKeyNot()`; use explicit columns like `where('id', ...)`.
- Do not use `Model::query()->create()`; use `Model::create()`.
- When migrations add columns, update model `$fillable` where applicable.
- Never chain migration generator commands with `&&` or `;`; run each command separately to avoid timestamp collisions.

## Observers and Providers

- Register model observers with PHP attributes on the model:
  - `#[ObservedBy([SomeObserver::class])]`
- Avoid registering observers in `AppServiceProvider` unless there is a strict exception.

## Project-Specific Alignment

- Keep patient identity semantics explicit:
  - `users.id` represents patient user identity in some tables.
  - `patient_profiles.id` represents clinical patient profile identity in others.
- Preserve workspace scoping (`workspace_id`) and role boundaries (`admin`, `professional`, `patient`) in all query and policy changes.
